<dl id="s17027av"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="us17" href="#s17027av">Ithaca: </a><a href="../../FF/unbs/s17all.htm#s17027av">sector 27(av)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> magnitude = brightness <small>Red</small></blockquote> <dd class="well"> <ul class="list-inline" id="s17027av"><li>Ulysses </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/lexs.htm#s17027av">2021</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/s86.htm#s17027av">2017</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/s86.htm#s17027av">1986 (17.1105f)</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/l22s.htm#s17027av">1922</a> </li><li><ms href="#s17027av">MS missing (TS-B)</ms> </li><li><a name="sd3" href="../udra/u17da.htm#sd3">Usage</a> </li><li><a href="../../ulex/s/sd3.htm#s17027av">Draft: 17.3</a></li> </ul> <blockquote class="sources">To facilitate the observation of stars of varying brilliancy, they have been classified in order of <mark>magnitude</mark>, according to their apparent <mark>brightness</mark>, and since the dimensions of these distant suns are almost wholly unknown to us, the most luminous stars were naturally denoted as of first magnitude, those which were a little less bright of the second, and so on. <small> Camille Flammarion, <a name="CFAA" href="/udra/udex.htm#CFAA"><cite title="source">Astronomy for Amateurs</cite></a> (1904), 56</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
